"Zhou T., Gong D., Li J., Li B.","Detecting and understanding the multi-decadal variability of the East Asian Summer Monsoon - Recent progress and state of affairs",2009,"Meteorologische Zeitschrift","18","4",,"455","467",,,10.1127/0941-2948/2009/0396,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77949385603&partnerID=40&md5=09a7bf12539b88ac33d57f935feca19f","LASG, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China; State Key Laboratory of Earth Surface Processes and Resource Ecology, Beijing Normal University, Beijing, China; LaSW, Chinese Academy of Meteorology Sciences, China Meteorology Administration, Beijing, China","Zhou, T., LASG, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China; Gong, D., State Key Laboratory of Earth Surface Processes and Resource Ecology, Beijing Normal University, Beijing, China; Li, J., LaSW, Chinese Academy of Meteorology Sciences, China Meteorology Administration, Beijing, China; Li, B., LASG, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China","East Asia is dominated by a typical monsoon climate. The East Asian summer monsoon (EASM) exhibits considerable variability on a wide range of time scales during the 20th century. A substantial portion is the multi-decadal variability. Over the recent decades, the EASM has been weakening from the end of the 1970s which results in a ""southern China flood and northern China drought"" rainfall pattern. Understanding the mechanisms responsible for the weakening tendency has been a challenge for climate research community. Examinations on the long-term change of the EASM during the 20th century find no significant trends, indicating the pronounced weakening tendency of the EASM in recent decades is unprecedented. After documenting the prominent features of the interdecadal climate transition, a review is presented in this paper on the proposed explanations to the observed changes. The proposed factors include the Indian Ocean and far western Pacific warming, the tropical central-eastern Pacific warming, the weakening sensible heat source over the Tibetan Plateau, and the aerosol forcing, as well as internal variability. While parts of the monsoon circulation changes can be explained in terms of the proposed mechanisms, it is still beyond the scope of our current knowledge to present a complete picture. Much remains to be learned about the mechanisms that produce such multi-decadal changes in the EASM, but it seems still unclear whether human activities and global warming are playing significant roles. © by Gebrüder Borntraeger 2009.",,"Aerosol forcing; Climate research; Climate transition; Decadal change; Decadal variability; East Asia; East Asian summer monsoon; Eastern pacific; Human activities; Indian ocean; Interdecadal; Internal variability; Long-term changes; Monsoon circulations; Monsoon climate; Northern China; Rainfall patterns; Recent progress; Sensible heat; Southern China; State of affairs; Tibetan Plateau; Time-scales; Western Pacific; Global warming; Rain; Wind effects; Ocean currents; aerosol; atmospheric circulation; climate change; decadal variation; monsoon; summer; wind; China; Far East; Indian Ocean; Qinghai-Xizang Plateau",,,,,,"ALLAN, R.J., ANSELL, T.J., A new globally complete monthly historical mean sea level pressure data set (HadSLP2): 1850-2004 (2006) J. Climate, 19, pp. 5816-5842; ARCHER, C.L., CALDEIRA, K., Historical trends in the jet streams (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett, 35, pp. L08803; BARLOW, M., CULLEN, H., LYON, B., Drought in Central and Southwest Asia: La Niña, the Warm Pool, and Indian Ocean Precipitation (2002) J. Climate, 15, pp. 697-700; BARLOW, M., WHEELER, M., LYON, B., CULLEN, H., Modulation of daily precipitation over southwest Asia by the Madden-Julian oscillation (2005) Mon. Wea. Rev, 133, pp. 3579-3594; BARLOW, M., HOELL, A., COLBY, F., Examining the wintertime response to tropical convection over the east